            ✅ THE 02 -> 04 INTERLOCK IS REAL, AND IT IS NOW MEASURED RATHER THAN CLAIMED. This is
            the FIRST of the plan's three interlocks to survive being checked, and the score is worth
            keeping: 07 planning on 01's one line was measurably FALSE (01 has eleven node types and
            not one is a breaker), 05 feeding readings into 01 was FALSE at both ends (05 ships no
            meter, 01 has no meters), and both were LIVE in the root README until today. This one
            holds. Rule #17 says an interlock in a plan is a HYPOTHESIS, so it was driven, not read:
              require 02/build/engine.js + curves.js from a 04 shaped call
              relay = { family: 'ge850-ieee', shape: 'extremely-inverse', pickup: 100, tdm: 2 }
              TCC.tripTime(relay, 500)  ->  2.5934 s
            GE's manual p.4-124 publishes "will not occur before 2.59 s" for exactly those settings.
            02 already exports everything device 51 needs: tripTime, multiple, resetTime, curvePoints,
            plus named vendor families. 04 writes no curve math.
            🔑 AND THE REFUSAL SURVIVES THE REUSE, which matters more than the saved code: calling
            tripTime with a generic family 'ieee' still THROWS ("unknown curve family: ieee. Families
            are named per vendor on purpose."). 04 inherits 02's refusal for free rather than
            laundering it away. An interlock that carried the code but dropped the refusal would be a
            downgrade.
            ⚠ WHAT THE INTERLOCK DOES NOT COVER: device 50 is NOT in 02 and should not be. An
            instantaneous element is a THRESHOLD, not a curve; 02 models curves. 04 builds 50 itself.

            🔴 SOURCES.md CARRIED A FALSE PROVENANCE CLAIM, IN PROSE, THREE LINES UNDER THE TABLE THAT
            DISPROVED IT. It said "The top three rows were read directly at the publisher's own PDF."
            The table says row 1 (GE 850, docs.ips.us) is a MIRROR and row 3 (SEL-351S) is a MIRROR
            read at a UNIVERSITY COURSE HANDOUT. Only row 2 is a publisher read. Corrected, and left
            visible.
            HOW IT SURVIVED IS THE REUSABLE PART. Pattern #10 was learned when 02's SOURCES.md made
            this IDENTICAL claim two lines above a distributor's URL. The fix was to stop trusting
            prose and add a machine checked field, the `Read at` column. **The column was added and
            the prose it was meant to replace was left standing**, so the false sentence went on
            sitting directly beneath its own correction. The gate cannot see it: check_sources.py
            asserts every row HAS a provenance value, not that the paragraph agrees with the column.
            ⇒ WHEN YOU REPLACE A PROSE CLAIM WITH A CHECKED FIELD, DELETE THE PROSE. Swept all six
            SOURCES.md for the phrase; 04 was the only one still carrying it.

